@chief tp
Assuming they have a flatbed, and can load it up before getting caught. You overestimate the complexity of car thieves. They go for the easiest possible payoff. Having a flatbed is too traceable, to big an initial investment. Easier to just sit in a public place with a receiver antenna and clone people's fobs, then walk off with cars with zero chance of being caught, since it looks like the thief is the legitimate driver to the average passerby. It costs almost nothing to make such a setup, and the security on the electronic side for cars is pretty crap.

As for cloning it, they can still clone it without you pressing unlock. The part for the immobilizer is always active. Missing the unlock command just means they need to slim-jim your door instead of getting in without any fuss.Ôªø

@CJ Colvin Speaking of straight 6 I might swap in a 292 Chevy straight 6 in my 1983 3/4 ton dually in place of the 454.....

Keep the 454 just in case.

Also if ford wanted performance but still better fuel economy, they should ditch the V6 and bring back the straight 6 for Mustangs with turboÔªø

